              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 text-emerald-900">Legislative Session Surges</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">
                When the Washington State Legislature is in session (January through April in odd years, January through March in even years), downtown Olympia's daytime population swells by an estimated <strong>10,000-15,000 people</strong>. Staffers, legislators, lobbyists, and visitors flood Capitol Way and the surrounding blocks. This population influx increases foot traffic, parking lot congestion, and property crime opportunities -- particularly vehicle break-ins and theft from businesses near the Capitol.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-600 p-6 rounded-r-lg">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 text-amber-900">Protest & Demonstration Activity</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">
                The Capitol Campus is a focal point for political demonstrations of all kinds. From large-scale organized marches to spontaneous gatherings, protest activity can escalate rapidly and spill into surrounding commercial areas. Businesses along Capitol Way, 4th Avenue, and the downtown corridor frequently request temporary surveillance during high-tension legislative periods, especially around contentious votes and budget sessions.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

